value: aava_1.0_score
description

The AAVA 2.0 metadata represents a significant structural evolution from AAVA 1.0 while preserving core semantic meaning. The workflow definition has been restructured with enhanced hierarchy and agent metadata but introduces some compatibility concerns.
Core workflow concept preserved: Both versions define a 3-agent data integration workflow for technical specifications model updates and functional testing. Business purpose remains identical.
Agent purposes maintain semantic alignment: DI_Data_Technical_Specification_SN agent retains same core responsibility for creating technical specification documents from JIRA Confluence DDL inputs.
DI_Delta_Model_Changes_SN agent preserves data model evolution analysis functionality across both versions with identical business logic requirements.
DI_Functional_Test_Cases_SN agent maintains same test case generation responsibilities from JIRA specifications in both versions.
Major structural reorganization detected: AAVA 1.0 uses flat workflow structure while AAVA 2.0 introduces nested workFlowDetail object hierarchy.
Workflow identifier restructured: workflowId (line 2) renamed to workFlowDetail.id (line 3) with value change from 1594 to 2147.
Workflow name restructured: workflowName (line 3) moved to workFlowDetail.name (line 4) with formatting change from DI_DataSpecs_Modelupdates_SN to 'DI DataSpecs Modelupdates SN'.
Agent array restructuring: AAVA 1.0 'nodes' array (line 4) replaced with 'workflowAgents' array (line 6) indicating semantic shift from generic nodes to specific agent entities.
Agent naming evolution: agentName field (line 6) replaced with name field (line 8) removing 'agent' prefix for cleaner naming convention.
Model specification enhancement: model field (line 7) replaced with modelDeploymentName (line 9) with version upgrade from 'gpt-4' to 'gpt-4.1'.
Tool reference restructuring: tools array (line 8) replaced with toolReferences array (line 11) suggesting shift from direct tool embedding to reference-based architecture.
Tool array content change: AAVA 1.0 contains 'DI_Github_File_Writer_Z' tool while AAVA 2.0 toolReferences array is empty indicating potential tool configuration externalization.
Agent identification enhancement: AAVA 2.0 introduces agentId field (line 7) providing unique numeric identifiers (3885 3474 3545) absent in AAVA 1.0.
Task structure preserved: Both versions maintain identical task object structure with description and expectedOutput fields containing same detailed specifications.
AAVA 1.0 JSON syntax validation: Valid JSON structure with proper bracket closure array formatting and string escaping. No syntax errors detected.
AAVA 1.0 internal consistency: All agent references tools and task structures are logically consistent. No orphaned references or type mismatches.
AAVA 2.0 JSON syntax validation: Valid JSON structure with proper nested object hierarchy and array formatting. No syntax errors detected.
AAVA 2.0 internal consistency: Agent IDs are unique toolReferences arrays are properly initialized and workFlowDetail structure is logically sound.
AAVA 2.0 minor inconsistency: Empty toolReferences arrays suggest incomplete migration or externalized tool configuration which may impact runtime behavior.
Backward compatibility risk: Field name changes (workflowId to workFlowDetail.id agentName to name) may break existing parsers and downstream systems expecting AAVA 1.0 structure.
Metadata versioning concern: No explicit version indicators in either schema making it difficult to programmatically distinguish AAVA 1.0 from AAVA 2.0 at runtime.
Tool configuration gap: Empty toolReferences in AAVA 2.0 compared to populated tools array in AAVA 1.0 may indicate incomplete migration or missing tool binding configuration.
ID value changes: Workflow ID change from 1594 to 2147 and introduction of agent IDs suggests these may be environment-specific rather than schema-intrinsic values.
Model version implications: Upgrade from gpt-4 to gpt-4.1 in modelDeploymentName may have functional implications not captured in metadata structure alone.

Content preservation: All task descriptions expectedOutput specifications and instructional content remain identical between versions indicating successful semantic preservation during structural evolution.
